# iree-runtime-dist artifact metadata

This directory (`share/iree-runtime-dist/`) holds the machine-readable metadata and the smoke
module shipped with the `@VARIANT@/@PLATFORM@` build of the IREE runtime, version `@IREE_VERSION@`.

## Path convention (stable contract)

Every file here lives at `share/iree-runtime-dist/<name>` under the extraction/install prefix.
This relative layout is a **stable contract** — rely on it directly from any build system
(Gradle, Python, Rust, …); you do not need CMake to locate these files.

| File | What it is |
|---|---|
| `manifest.json` | build/pairing provenance (`schema_version: 2`) |
| `element_types.json` | `IREE_HAL_ELEMENT_TYPE_*` name → enriched entry, generated from IREE's headers |
| `element_types.schema.json` | JSON Schema (2020-12) for `element_types.json` |
| `status_codes.json` | `iree_status_code_t` name → enriched entry, generated from IREE's headers |
| `status_codes.schema.json` | JSON Schema (2020-12) for `status_codes.json` |
| `add.vmfb` | smoke module: `@add(tensor<4xf32>, tensor<4xf32>) -> tensor<4xf32>`, compiled by the paired compiler |
| `README.md` | this file |
| `TSAN.md` | *(tsan variant only)* the ThreadSanitizer consumer runbook |

`BUILDINFO` (at the prefix root, not here) is the same provenance as `manifest.json` in a
line-oriented `key=value` form for shell consumers.

## JSON schema

`element_types.json` and `status_codes.json` are each a versioned, self-describing object — not a
flat name-to-int map. Both carry a top-level `schema_version`.

`element_types.json` also carries an `encoding` block describing how IREE packs each value
(`value = (numerical_type << 24) | bit_count`) plus the `numerical_types` enum (`INTEGER`,
`INTEGER_SIGNED`, `INTEGER_UNSIGNED`, `BOOLEAN`, `FLOAT`, `FLOAT_IEEE`, `FLOAT_BRAIN`,
`FLOAT_COMPLEX`, the FP8 variants, …), and its `element_types` object maps each NAME to an entry
with `value`, `hex` (`value` formatted `0x%08x`), `numerical_type`, `category` (a coarser bucket:
`integer` / `float` / `boolean` / `complex` / `opaque`), `signed` (`true`/`false`/`null`), and
`bit_count`:

```json
{
  "schema_version": 1,
  "encoding": { "formula": "value = (numerical_type << 24) | bit_count",
                "numerical_types": { "INTEGER": 16, "INTEGER_SIGNED": 17, "FLOAT_IEEE": 33, "...": "..." } },
  "element_types": {
    "FLOAT_32": { "value": 553648160, "hex": "0x21000020", "numerical_type": "FLOAT_IEEE",
                  "category": "float", "signed": null, "bit_count": 32 }
  }
}
```

`status_codes.json` carries `schema_version` and a `status_codes` object mapping each NAME to
`{ "value": <int>, "description": "<one-line human meaning>" }` (`description` is curated,
informational text — not part of the value contract).

Every field except `description` is derived authoritatively from the shipped runtime's own
headers, not hand-transcribed — generate your bindings from these rather than transcribing (e.g.
`FLOAT_32 = 553648160 = 0x21000020`). The counts (24 element types, 19 status codes) are not part
of the contract; iterate the object. `element_types.schema.json` and `status_codes.schema.json`
(JSON Schema 2020-12, per-field `description`s) ship alongside the data for validation and editor
tooling.

**The boundary:** these per-type properties (value, numerical type, signedness, bit width) are
authoritative — but *which* IREE type best matches one of your own native types (e.g. choosing
between sign-agnostic `INT_32`, signed `SINT_32`, and unsigned `UINT_32` for your own `int`) is
your integration's policy decision, not something this data can make for you.

`manifest.json` is a structured object and carries its own `schema_version` and `notes.*` fields;
read those notes before interpreting `glibc_build`, `sanitizer`, or `vm_bytecode_version`.
